# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jinja-templating
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jinja-templating/comparison-of-web-template-engines] The following table lists the various web template engines used in Web template systems and a brief rundown of their features.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] The Jinja template engine allows customization of tags, filters (for formatting or transforming values), tests (for evaluating conditions), and globals.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] Also, unlike the Django template engine, Jinja allows the template designer to call functions with arguments on objects.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] Jinja is the default template engine for Flask, as well as Home Assistant's Automations.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] It is also used by Ansible, Trac, and Salt.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] It is also used to make SQL macros, for example for use with dbt.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] Jinja, like Smarty, also ships with an easy-to-use filter system similar to the Unix pipeline.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] The syntax for printing output in Jinja is using the double curly braces, for example `{{ Hello, World! }}`.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] Statements which set variables in jinja or those which do not have an output can be wrapped within `{%` and `%}`, using the `set` keyword.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] For example `{% set foo = 42 %}` sets a variable called `foo` with a value of 42.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] Similar to above, comments in jinja can be written using a number sign (`#`) instead of a percentage (`%`), for example, `{# helpful comment #}`.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] The syntax for creating a filter in Jinja is a vertical bar (`|`), for example `{{ variable|filter }}`.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] A variable can have multiple filters, for example `{{ variable|filter|filter }}`).
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] The syntax for creating a test in Jinja is the keyword `is` as well as the conditions for evaluating the validity of a test, such as for example `{% if variable is divisibleby 10 %}do something{% endif %}`).
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] For loops can be used to iterate over sequences, while retaining their object properties.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] The following example demonstrates iterating over a list of users with `username` and `password` fields.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] Although `break` and `continue` are not allowed inside loops, sequences can be filtered.
[src:jinja-templating/jinja-template-engine] Note the minus sign (`-`) after the tag `{%`: If you add a minus sign (`-`) to the start or end of a block (e.g. a For tag), a comment, or a variable expression, the whitespaces before or after that block will be removed.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] A **template processor** (also known as a **template engine** or **template parser**) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] The language that the templates are written in is known as a **template language** or **templating language**.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] For purposes of this article, a result document is any kind of formatted output, including documents, web pages, or source code (in source code generation), either in whole or in fragments.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] A template engine is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework, and may be used also as a preprocessor or filter.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] Template engines typically include features common to most high-level programming languages, with an emphasis on features for processing plain text.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] The templating languages are generally simple substitution-only languages, in contrast to the more sophisticated facilities in full-blown template processors, but may contain some logic.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] Simple examples include ‘printf’ print format strings, found in many programming languages, and snippets, found in a number of text editors and source code editors.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] In word processors, templates are a common feature, while automatic filling in of the templates is often referred to as mail merge.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] An illustrative example of the complementary nature of parsing and templating is the `s` (substitute) command in the sed text processor, originating from search-and-replace in the ed text editor.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] For example, `s/(cat|dog)s?/\1s/g` replaces all occurrences of "cat" or "dog" with "cats" or "dogs", without duplicating an existing "s": `(cat|dog)` is the 1st (and only) sub-expression in the regexp, and `\1` in the format string substitutes this into the output.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] This may be a relational database, a source file such as XML, an alternate format of flat file database, a spreadsheet or any of other various sources of preformatted data.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] Some template processing systems are limited in the types of data that can be used.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] Others are designed for maximum flexibility and allow many different types of data.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] Additionally some template engines allow additional configuration options.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] These may consist of an entire document or a document fragment.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] Template processing is used in various contexts for different purposes.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] The specific purpose is ordinarily contingent upon the software application or template engine in use.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] However, the flexibility of template processing systems often enables unconventional uses for purposes not originally intended by the original designers.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] A **template engine** is a specific kind of template processing module that exhibits all of the major features of a modern programming language.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] The term *template engine* evolved as a generalized description of programming languages whose primary or exclusive purpose was to process templates and data to output text.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] The use of this term is most notably applied to web development using a web template system, and it is also applied to other contexts as well.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] Document generation frameworks typically use template processing as the central model for generating documents.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] A web template engine processes web templates and source data (typically from a relational database) to produce one or more output web pages or page fragments.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] It is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] Currently, template processing software is most frequently used in the context of development for the web.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] XSLT is a template processing model designed by W3C.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] It is designed primarily for transformations on XML data (into web documents or other output).
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] Programming languages such as Perl, Python, PHP, Ruby, C#, Java, and Go support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] JavaServer Pages, Active Server Pages, Genshi (for Python), and eRuby are examples of template engines designed specifically for web application development.
[src:jinja-templating/template-processor] Moreover, template processing is sometimes included as a sub-feature of software packages like text editors, IDEs and relational database management systems.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This document describes the syntax and semantics of the template engine and will be most useful as reference to those creating Jinja templates.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] As the template engine is very flexible, the configuration from the application can be slightly different from the code presented here in terms of delimiters and behavior of undefined values.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Jinja can generate any text-based format (HTML, XML, CSV, LaTeX, etc.).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] A Jinja template doesn’t need to have a specific extension: `.html`, `.xml`, or any other extension is just fine.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] A template contains **variables** and/or **expressions**, which get replaced with values when a template is *rendered*; and **tags**, which control the logic of the template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The template syntax is heavily inspired by Django and Python.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Below is a minimal template that illustrates a few basics using the default Jinja configuration.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The following example shows the default configuration settings.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] An application developer can change the syntax configuration from `{% foo %}` to `<% foo %>`, or something similar.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Line Statements and Comments are also possible, though they don’t have default prefix characters.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] To use them, set `line_statement_prefix` and `line_comment_prefix` when creating the `Environment`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] As stated above, any file can be loaded as a template, regardless of file extension.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Adding a `.jinja` extension, like `user.html.jinja` may make it easier for some IDEs or editor plugins, but is not required.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Autoescaping, introduced later, can be applied based on file extension, so you’ll need to take the extra suffix into account in that case.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Another good heuristic for identifying templates is that they are in a `templates` folder, regardless of extension.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Template variables are defined by the context dictionary passed to the template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] You can mess around with the variables in templates provided they are passed in by the application.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Variables may have attributes or elements on them you can access too.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] What attributes a variable has depends heavily on the application providing that variable.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] You can use a dot (`.`) to access attributes of a variable in addition to the standard Python `__getitem__` “subscript” syntax (`[]`).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] It’s important to know that the outer double-curly braces are *not* part of the variable, but the print statement.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If you access variables inside tags don’t put the braces around them.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If a variable or attribute does not exist, you will get back an undefined value.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] What you can do with that kind of value depends on the application configuration: the default behavior is to evaluate to an empty string if printed or iterated over, and to fail for every other operation.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This is important if an object has an item and attribute with the same name.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Additionally, the `attr()` filter only looks up attributes.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Variables can be modified by **filters**.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Filters are separated from the variable by a pipe symbol (`|`) and may have optional arguments in parentheses.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The output of one filter is applied to the next.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For example, `{{ name|striptags|title }}` will remove all HTML Tags from variable `name` and title-case the output (`title(striptags(name))`).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Filters that accept arguments have parentheses around the arguments, just like a function call.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For example: `{{ listx|join(', ') }}` will join a list with commas (`str.join(', ', listx)`).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The List of Builtin Filters below describes all the builtin filters.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Beside filters, there are also so-called “tests” available.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Tests can be used to test a variable against a common expression.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] To test a variable or expression, you add `is` plus the name of the test after the variable.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For example, to find out if a variable is defined, you can do `name is defined`, which will then return true or false depending on whether `name` is defined in the current template context.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If the test only takes one argument, you can leave out the parentheses.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The List of Builtin Tests below describes all the builtin tests.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If an application configures Jinja to `trim_blocks`, the first newline after a template tag is removed automatically (like in PHP).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The `lstrip_blocks` option can also be set to strip tabs and spaces from the beginning of a line to the start of a block.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] With both `trim_blocks` and `lstrip_blocks` disabled (the default), block tags on their own lines will be removed, but a blank line will remain and the spaces in the content will be preserved.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] You can also strip whitespace in templates by hand.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This will yield all elements without whitespace between them.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If `seq` was a list of numbers from `1` to `9`, the output would be `123456789`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If Line Statements are enabled, they strip leading whitespace automatically up to the beginning of the line.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] By default, Jinja also removes trailing newlines.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] To keep single trailing newlines, configure Jinja to `keep_trailing_newline`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] You must not add whitespace between the tag and the minus sign.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] It is sometimes desirable – even necessary – to have Jinja ignore parts it would otherwise handle as variables or blocks.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For example, if, with the default syntax, you want to use `{{` as a raw string in a template and not start a variable, you have to use a trick.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For bigger sections, it makes sense to mark a block `raw`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Minus sign at the end of `{% raw -%}` tag cleans all the spaces and newlines preceding the first character of your raw data.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If line statements are enabled by the application, it’s possible to mark a line as a statement.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The line statement prefix can appear anywhere on the line as long as no text precedes it.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Since Jinja 2.2, line-based comments are available as well.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The most powerful part of Jinja is template inheritance.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Template inheritance allows you to build a base “skeleton” template that contains all the common elements of your site and defines **blocks** that child templates can override.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] It’s easiest to understand it by starting with an example.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This template, which we’ll call `base.html`, defines a simple HTML skeleton document that you might use for a simple two-column page.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] In this example, the `{% block %}` tags define four blocks that child templates can fill in.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] All the `block` tag does is tell the template engine that a child template may override those placeholders in the template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] `block` tags can be inside other blocks such as `if`, but they will always be executed regardless of if the `if` block is actually rendered.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The `{% extends %}` tag is the key here.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] It tells the template engine that this template “extends” another template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] When the template system evaluates this template, it first locates the parent.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The extends tag should be the first tag in the template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Everything before it is printed out normally and may cause confusion.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For details about this behavior and how to take advantage of it, see Null-Default Fallback.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Also a block will always be filled in regardless of whether the surrounding condition is evaluated to be true or false.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The filename of the template depends on the template loader.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For example, the `FileSystemLoader` allows you to access other templates by giving the filename.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] But this behavior can depend on the application embedding Jinja.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Note that since the child template doesn’t define the `footer` block, the value from the parent template is used instead.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] You can’t define multiple `{% block %}` tags with the same name in the same template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This limitation exists because a block tag works in “both” directions.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] That is, a block tag doesn’t just provide a placeholder to fill - it also defines the content that fills the placeholder in the *parent*.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If there were two similarly-named `{% block %}` tags in a template, that template’s parent wouldn’t know which one of the blocks’ content to use.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] It’s possible to render the contents of the parent block by calling `super()`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] In the case of multiple levels of `{% extends %}`, `super` references may be chained (as in `super.super()`) to skip levels in the inheritance tree.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Rendering `child.tmpl` will give `body: Hi from child.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Rendering `grandchild2.tmpl` will give `body: Hi from grandchild2.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] However, the name after the `endblock` word must match the block name.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Blocks can be nested for more complex layouts.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This example would output empty `<li>` items because `item` is unavailable inside the block.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The reason for this is that if the block is replaced by a child template, a variable would appear that was not defined in the block or passed to the context.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] When overriding a block, the `scoped` modifier does not have to be provided.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] They must be overridden at some point, but not necessarily by the direct child template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Required blocks may only contain space and comments, and they cannot be rendered directly.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Rendering `page.txt` or `issue.txt` will raise `TemplateRuntimeError` because they don’t override the `body` block.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Rendering `bug_report.txt` will succeed because it does override the block.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] When combined with `scoped`, the `required` modifier must be placed *after* the scoped modifier.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] `extends`, `include`, and `import` can take a template object instead of the name of a template to load.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This could be useful in some advanced situations, since you can use Python code to load a template first and pass it in to `render`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Note how `extends` is passed the variable with the template object that was passed to `render`, instead of a string.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] When generating HTML from templates, there’s always a risk that a variable will include characters that affect the resulting HTML.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] 2. automatically escaping everything by default.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] What is used depends on the application configuration.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If manual escaping is enabled, it’s **your** responsibility to escape variables if needed.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If you have a variable that *may* include any of the following chars (`>`, `<`, `&`, or `"`) you **SHOULD** escape it unless the variable contains well-formed and trusted HTML.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] When automatic escaping is enabled, everything is escaped by default except for values explicitly marked as safe.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If a string that you marked safe is passed through other Python code that doesn’t understand that mark, it may get lost.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Be aware of when your data is marked safe and how it is processed before arriving at the template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If a value has been escaped but is not marked safe, auto-escaping will still take place and result in double-escaped characters.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If you know you have data that is already safe but not marked, be sure to wrap it in `Markup` or use the `|safe` filter.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Jinja functions (macros, `super`, `self.BLOCKNAME`) always return template data that is marked as safe.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] String literals in templates with automatic escaping are considered unsafe because native Python strings are not safe.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] A control structure refers to all those things that control the flow of a program - conditionals (i.e. if/elif/else), for-loops, as well as things like macros and blocks.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] With the default syntax, control structures appear inside `{% ... %}` blocks.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Python dicts may not be in the order you want to display them in.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If order matters, use the `|dictsort` filter.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Since Jinja 2.1, an extra `cycle` helper exists that allows loop-unbound cycling.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For more information, have a look at the List of Global Functions.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Unlike in Python, it’s not possible to `break` or `continue` in a loop.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] You can, however, filter the sequence during iteration, which allows you to skip items.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The advantage is that the special `loop` variable will count correctly; thus not counting the users not iterated over.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Note that, in Python, `else` blocks are executed whenever the corresponding loop **did not** `break`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Since Jinja loops cannot `break` anyway, a slightly different behavior of the `else` keyword was chosen.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] It is also possible to use loops recursively.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This is useful if you are dealing with recursive data such as sitemaps or RDFa.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] To use loops recursively, you basically have to add the `recursive` modifier to the loop definition and call the `loop` variable with the new iterable where you want to recurse.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The `loop` variable always refers to the closest (innermost) loop.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If we have more than one level of loops, we can rebind the variable `loop` by writing `{% set outer_loop = loop %}` after the loop that we want to use recursively.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Please note that assignments in loops will be cleared at the end of the iteration and cannot outlive the loop scope.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Older versions of Jinja had a bug where in some circumstances it appeared that assignments would work.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] See Assignments for more information about how to deal with this.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The `if` statement in Jinja is comparable with the Python if statement.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For multiple branches, `elif` and `else` can be used like in Python.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If can also be used as an inline expression and for loop filtering.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Macros are comparable with functions in regular programming languages.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] They are useful to put often used idioms into reusable functions to not repeat yourself (“DRY”).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If the macro was defined in a different template, you have to import it first.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If more positional arguments are passed to the macro than accepted by the macro, they end up in the special `varargs` variable as a list of values.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Like `varargs` but for keyword arguments.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] All unconsumed keyword arguments are stored in this special variable.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If the macro was called from a call tag, the caller is stored in this variable as a callable macro.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Macros also expose some of their internal details.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] A tuple of the names of arguments the macro accepts.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This is `true` if the macro accepts extra keyword arguments (i.e.: accesses the special `kwargs` variable).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This is `true` if the macro accepts extra positional arguments (i.e.: accesses the special `varargs` variable).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This is `true` if the macro accesses the special `caller` variable and may be called from a call tag.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If a macro name starts with an underscore, it’s not exported and can’t be imported.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Due to how scopes work in Jinja, a macro in a child template does not override a macro in a parent template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The following will output “LAYOUT”, not “CHILD”.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] In some cases it can be useful to pass a macro to another macro.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For this purpose, you can use the special `call` block.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] It’s also possible to pass arguments back to the call block.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This makes it useful as a replacement for loops.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Generally speaking, a call block works exactly like a macro without a name.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Filter sections allow you to apply regular Jinja filters on a block of template data.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Inside code blocks, you can also assign values to variables.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Assignments at top level (outside of blocks, macros or loops) are exported from the template like top level macros and can be imported by other templates.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Please keep in mind that it is not possible to set variables inside a block and have them show up outside of it.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The only exception to that rule are if statements which do not introduce a scope.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] It is not possible with Jinja syntax to do this.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Note that the `obj.attr` notation in the `set` tag is only allowed for namespace objects; attempting to assign an attribute on any other object will raise an exception.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] It’s possible to use `set` as a block to assign the content of the block to a variable.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This can be used to create multi-line strings, since Jinja doesn’t support Python’s triple quotes (`"""`, `'''`).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Instead of using an equals sign and a value, you only write the variable name, and everything until `{% endset %}` is captured.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Filters applied to the variable name will be applied to the block’s content.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Changed in version 2.10: Block assignment supports filters.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The `extends` tag can be used to extend one template from another.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] You can have multiple `extends` tags in a file, but only one of them may be executed at a time.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] See the section about Template Inheritance above.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Blocks are used for inheritance and act as both placeholders and replacements at the same time.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] They are documented in detail in the Template Inheritance section.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The `include` tag renders another template and outputs the result into the current template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The included template has access to context of the current template by default.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Use `without context` to use a separate context instead.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] `with context` is also valid, but is the default behavior.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The included template can `extend` another template and override blocks in that template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] However, the current template cannot override any blocks that the included template outputs.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Use `ignore missing` to ignore the statement if the template does not exist.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] It must be placed *before* a context visibility statement.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If a list of templates is given, each will be tried in order until one is not missing.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This can be used with `ignore missing` to ignore if none of the templates exist.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] A variable, with either a template name or template object, can also be passed to the statement.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Jinja supports putting often used code into macros.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] These macros can go into different templates and get imported from there.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This works similarly to the import statements in Python.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] It’s important to know that imports are cached and imported templates don’t have access to the current template variables, just the globals by default.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For more details about context behavior of imports and includes, see Import Context Behavior.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] You can import a complete template into a variable or request specific macros / exported variables from it.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The easiest and most flexible way to access a template’s variables and macros is to import the whole template module into a variable.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Macros and variables starting with one or more underscores are private and cannot be imported.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Changed in version 2.4: If a template object was passed to the template context, you can import from that object.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] By default, included templates are passed the current context and imported templates are not.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The reason for this is that imports, unlike includes, are cached; as imports are often used just as a module that holds macros.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This behavior can be changed explicitly: by adding `with context` or `without context` to the import/include directive, the current context can be passed to the template and caching is disabled automatically.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] In Jinja 2.0, the context that was passed to the included template did not include variables defined in the template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The included template `render_box.html` is *not* able to access `box` in Jinja 2.0.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] As of Jinja 2.1, `render_box.html` *is* able to do so.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Jinja allows basic expressions everywhere.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] These work very similarly to regular Python; even if you’re not working with Python you should feel comfortable with it.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The simplest form of expressions are literals.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Literals are representations for Python objects such as strings and numbers.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Everything between two double or single quotes is a string.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] They are useful whenever you need a string in the template (e.g. as arguments to function calls and filters, or just to extend or include a template).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Integers are whole numbers without a decimal part.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The ‘_’ character can be used to separate groups for legibility.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Floating point numbers can be written using a ‘.’ as a decimal mark.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] They can also be written in scientific notation with an upper or lower case ‘e’ to indicate the exponent part.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The ‘_’ character can be used to separate groups for legibility, but cannot be used in the exponent part.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Everything between two brackets is a list.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Lists are useful for storing sequential data to be iterated over.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Tuples are like lists that cannot be modified (“immutable”).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] If a tuple only has one item, it must be followed by a comma (`('1-tuple',)`).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Tuples are usually used to represent items of two or more elements.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] See the list example above for more details.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] A dict in Python is a structure that combines keys and values.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Keys must be unique and always have exactly one value.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Dicts are rarely used in templates; they are useful in some rare cases such as the `xmlattr()` filter.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] `true` is always true and `false` is always false.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The special constants `true`, `false`, and `none` are indeed lowercase.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Because that caused confusion in the past, (`True` used to expand to an undefined variable that was considered false), all three can now also be written in title case (`True`, `False`, and `None`).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] However, for consistency, (all Jinja identifiers are lowercase) you should use the lowercase versions.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Jinja allows you to calculate with values.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This is rarely useful in templates but exists for completeness’ sake.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Usually the objects are numbers, but if both are strings or lists, you can concatenate them this way.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This, however, is not the preferred way to concatenate strings!
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For string concatenation, have a look-see at the `~` operator.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Subtract the second number from the first one.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The return value will be a floating point number.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Divide two numbers and return the truncated integer result.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Calculate the remainder of an integer division.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Multiply the left operand with the right one.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This can also be used to repeat a string multiple times.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Raise the left operand to the power of the right operand.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Unlike Python, chained pow is evaluated left to right.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Use parentheses in Jinja to be explicit about what order you want.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] It is usually preferable to do extended math in Python and pass the results to `render` rather than doing it in the template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This behavior may be changed in the future to match Python, if it’s possible to introduce an upgrade path.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] `true` if the left hand side is greater than the right hand side.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] `true` if the left hand side is greater or equal to the right hand side.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] `true` if the left hand side is lower than the right hand side.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] `true` if the left hand side is lower or equal to the right hand side.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For `if` statements, `for` filtering, and `if` expressions, it can be useful to combine multiple expressions.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For `x and y`, if `x` is false, then the value is `x`, else `y`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] In a boolean context, this will be treated as `True` if both operands are truthy.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For `x or y`, if `x` is true, then the value is `x`, else `y`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] In a boolean context, this will be treated as `True` if at least one operand is truthy.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] For `not x`, if `x` is false, then the value is `True`, else `False`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Prefer negating `is` and `in` using their infix notation: `foo is not bar` instead of `not foo is bar`; `foo not in bar` instead of `not foo in bar`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This is used to change evaluation order, or to make a long expression easier to read or less ambiguous.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Perform a sequence / mapping containment test.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Returns true if the left operand is contained in the right.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] Converts all operands into strings and concatenates them.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] `{{ "Hello " ~ name ~ "!" }}` would return (assuming `name` is set to `'John'`) `Hello John!`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] It is also possible to use inline `if` expressions.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The general syntax is `<do something> if <something is true> else <do something else>`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] You can also use any of the methods defined on a variable’s type.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] The value returned from the method invocation is used as the value of the expression.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p01] This works for methods on user-defined types.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return the absolute value of the argument.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] `foo|attr("bar")` works like `foo.bar`, but returns undefined instead of falling back to `foo["bar"]` if the attribute doesn’t exist.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] See Notes on subscriptions for more details.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] It works pretty much like `slice` just the other way round.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] It returns a list of lists with the given number of items.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If you provide a second parameter this is used to fill up missing items.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] The first character will be uppercase, all others lowercase.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Centers the value in a field of a given width.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] This will output the value of `my_variable` if the variable was defined, otherwise `'my_variable is not defined'`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Changed in version 2.11: It’s now possible to configure the `Environment` with `ChainableUndefined` to make the `default` filter work on nested elements and attributes that may contain undefined values in the chain without getting an `UndefinedError`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Sort a dict and yield (key, value) pairs.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Python dicts may not be in the order you want to display them in, so sort them first.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Replace the characters `&`, `<`, `>`, `'`, and `"` in the string with HTML-safe sequences.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Use this if you need to display text that might contain such characters in HTML.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If the object has an `__html__` method, it is called and the return value is assumed to already be safe for HTML.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] A `Markup` string with the escaped text.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Format the value like a ‘human-readable’ file size (i.e.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Per default decimal prefixes are used (Mega, Giga, etc.), if the second parameter is set to `True` the binary prefixes are used (Mebi, Gibi).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Convert the value into a floating point number.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If the conversion doesn’t work it will return `0.0`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] You can override this default using the first parameter.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] This will probably double escape variables.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Apply the given values to a printf-style format string, like `string % values`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] In most cases it should be more convenient and efficient to use the `%` operator or `str.format()`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Group a sequence of objects by an attribute using Python’s `itertools.groupby()`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] The attribute can use dot notation for nested access, like `"address.city"`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Unlike Python’s `groupby`, the values are sorted first so only one group is returned for each unique value.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] For example, a list of `User` objects with a `city` attribute can be rendered in groups.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] In this example, `grouper` refers to the `city` value of the group.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] `groupby` yields namedtuples of `(grouper, list)`, which can be used instead of the tuple unpacking above.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] `grouper` is the value of the attribute, and `list` is the items with that value.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] You can specify a `default` value to use if an object in the list does not have the given attribute.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Like the `sort()` filter, sorting and grouping is case-insensitive by default.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] The `key` for each group will have the case of the first item in that group of values.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] For example, if a list of users has cities `["CA", "NY", "ca"]`, the “CA” group will have two values.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] This can be disabled by passing `case_sensitive=True`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Changed in version 3.1: Added the `case_sensitive` parameter.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Sorting and grouping is case-insensitive by default, matching other filters that do comparisons.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Changed in version 3.0: Added the `default` parameter.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Changed in version 2.6: The attribute supports dot notation for nested access.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return a copy of the string with each line indented by 4 spaces.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] The first line and blank lines are not indented by default.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Changed in version 3.0: `width` can be a string.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Changed in version 2.10: Blank lines are not indented by default.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Rename the `indentfirst` argument to `first`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If the conversion doesn’t work it will return `0`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] You can also override the default base (10) in the second parameter, which handles input with prefixes such as 0b, 0o and 0x for bases 2, 8 and 16 respectively.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] The base is ignored for decimal numbers and non-string values.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return an iterator over the `(key, value)` items of a mapping.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] `x|items` is the same as `x.items()`, except if `x` is undefined an empty iterator is returned.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] This filter is useful if you expect the template to be rendered with an implementation of Jinja in another programming language that does not have a `.items()` method on its mapping type.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return a string which is the concatenation of the strings in the sequence.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Added in version 2.6: The `attribute` parameter was added.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return the number of items in a container.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If it was a string the returned list will be a list of characters.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Applies a filter on a sequence of objects or looks up an attribute.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] This is useful when dealing with lists of objects but you are really only interested in a certain value of it.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] The basic usage is mapping on an attribute.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Alternatively you can let it invoke a filter by passing the name of the filter and the arguments afterwards.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Changed in version 2.11.0: Added the `default` parameter.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return the largest item from the sequence.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return the smallest item from the sequence.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Filters a sequence of objects by applying a test to each object, and rejecting the objects with the test succeeding.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If no test is specified, each object will be evaluated as a boolean.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Filters a sequence of objects by applying a test to the specified attribute of each object, and rejecting the objects with the test succeeding.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If no test is specified, the attribute’s value will be evaluated as a boolean.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return a copy of the value with all occurrences of a substring replaced with a new one.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] The first argument is the substring that should be replaced, the second is the replacement string.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Reverse the object or return an iterator that iterates over it the other way round.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If you don’t specify a method `'common'` is used.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Note that even if rounded to 0 precision, a float is returned.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Mark the value as safe which means that in an environment with automatic escaping enabled this variable will not be escaped.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Filters a sequence of objects by applying a test to each object, and only selecting the objects with the test succeeding.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Filters a sequence of objects by applying a test to the specified attribute of each object, and only selecting the objects with the test succeeding.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Slice an iterator and return a list of lists containing those items.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If you pass it a second argument it’s used to fill missing values on the last iteration.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Sort an iterable using Python’s `sorted()`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] The sort is stable, it does not change the relative order of elements that compare equal.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] This makes it is possible to chain sorts on different attributes and ordering.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] As a shortcut to chaining when the direction is the same for all attributes, pass a comma separate list of attributes.
