[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return true if the object is a boolean value.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return whether the object is callable (i.e., some kind of function).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Note that classes are callable, as are instances of classes with a __call__() method.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] See the `default()` filter for a simple way to set undefined variables.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Check if a variable is divisible by a number.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Useful if a filter may be optionally available.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return true if the object is an integer.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Check if it’s possible to iterate over an object.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return true if the variable is lowercased.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return true if the object is a mapping (dict etc.).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return true if the variable is a number.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return true if the variable is a sequence.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Sequences are variables that are iterable.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Useful if a test may be optionally available.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Like `defined()` but the other way round.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return true if the variable is uppercased.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return a list containing an arithmetic progression of integers.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] When step is given, it specifies the increment (or decrement).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] These are exactly the valid indices for a list of 4 elements.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] This is useful to repeat a template block multiple times, e.g. to fill a list.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Generates some lorem ipsum for the template.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] By default, five paragraphs of HTML are generated with each paragraph between 20 and 100 words.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If html is False, regular text is returned.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] This is useful to generate simple contents for layout testing.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] A convenient alternative to dict literals.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Cycle through values by yielding them one at a time, then restarting once the end is reached.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Similar to `loop.cycle`, but can be used outside loops or across multiple loops.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] For example, render a list of folders and files in a list, alternating giving them “odd” and “even” classes.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Equivalent to the item that will be returned next time `next()` is called.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Return the current item, then advance `current` to the next item.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Resets the current item to the first item.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] A tiny helper that can be used to “join” multiple sections.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] A joiner is passed a string and will return that string every time it’s called, except the first time (in which case it returns an empty string).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] The main purpose of this is to allow carrying a value from within a loop body to an outer scope.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Changed in version 3.2: Namespace attributes can be assigned to in multiple assignment.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] The following sections cover the built-in Jinja extensions that may be enabled by an application.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] An application could also provide further extensions not covered by this documentation; in which case there should be a separate document explaining said extensions.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If the i18n Extension is enabled, it’s possible to mark text in the template as translatable.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Inside the block, no statements are allowed, only text and simple variable tags.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Variable tags can only be a name, not attribute access, filters, or other expressions.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] To use an expression, bind it to a name in the `trans` tag for use in the block.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] To bind more than one expression, separate each with a comma (`,`).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] To pluralize, specify both the singular and plural forms separated by the `pluralize` tag.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] By default, the first variable in a block is used to determine whether to use singular or plural form.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If that isn’t correct, specify the variable used for pluralizing as a parameter to `pluralize`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] When translating blocks of text, whitespace and linebreaks result in hard to read and error-prone translation strings.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] To avoid this, a trans block can be marked as trimmed, which will replace all linebreaks and the whitespace surrounding them with a single space and remove leading and trailing whitespace.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] This results in `This is %(book_title)s.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] You should read it!` in the translation file.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If trimming is enabled globally, the `notrimmed` modifier can be used to disable it for a block.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Added in version 2.10: The `trimmed` and `notrimmed` modifiers have been added.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If the translation depends on the context that the message appears in, the `pgettext` and `npgettext` functions take a `context` string as the first argument, which is used to select the appropriate translation.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] To specify a context with the `{% trans %}` tag, provide a string as the first token after `trans`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Added in version 3.1: A context can be passed to the `trans` tag to use `pgettext` and `npgettext`.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] To use placeholders, use the `format` filter.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Always use keyword arguments to `format`, as other languages may not use the words in the same order.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If New Style Gettext calls are activated, using placeholders is easier.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Formatting is part of the `gettext` call instead of using the `format` filter.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] The `ngettext` function’s format string automatically receives the count as a `num` parameter in addition to the given parameters.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If the expression-statement extension is loaded, a tag called `do` is available that works exactly like the regular variable expression (`{{ ... }}`); except it doesn’t print anything.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If the application enables the Loop Controls, it’s possible to use `break` and `continue` in loops.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] When `break` is reached, the loop is terminated; if `continue` is reached, the processing is stopped and continues with the next iteration.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Note that `loop.index` starts with 1, and `loop.index0` starts with 0 (See: For).
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If the Debug Extension is enabled, a `{% debug %}` tag will be available to dump the current context as well as the available filters and tests.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] This is useful to see what’s available to use in the template without setting up a debugger.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] The with statement makes it possible to create a new inner scope.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Variables set within this scope are not visible outside of the scope.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] Because it is common to set variables at the beginning of the scope, you can do that within the `with` statement.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] In Jinja versions before 2.9 the behavior of referencing one variable to another had some unintended consequences.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] In particular one variable could refer to another defined in the same with block’s opening statement.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] This caused issues with the cleaned up scoping behavior and has since been improved.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] In earlier Jinja versions the `b` attribute would refer to the results of the first attribute.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] In older versions of Jinja (before 2.9) it was required to enable this feature with an extension.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] If you want you can activate and deactivate the autoescaping from within the templates.
[src:jinja-templating/templates-p02] After an `endautoescape` the behavior is reverted to what it was before.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] A **web template system** in web publishing allows web designers and developers to work with *web templates* to automatically generate custom web pages, such as the results from a search.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] This reuses static web page elements while defining dynamic elements based on web request parameters.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Web templates support static content, providing basic structure and appearance.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Developers can implement templates from content management systems, web application frameworks, and HTML editors.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] The template and content resources are processed and combined by the template engine to mass-produce web documents, each with a similar visual format.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] For purposes of this article, web documents include any of various output formats for transmission over the web via HTTP, HTTPS, or another Internet protocol.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] A template processor (also known as a template engine or template parser) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] The language that the templates are written in is known as a template language or templating language.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] With the model typically held in a relational database, the remaining components of the MVC architecture are the control and view.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] In the simplest of systems these two are not separated.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] However, adapting the separation of concerns principle one can completely decouple the relationships.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] A web browser and web server are a client–server architecture.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Sites often also use a web cache to improve performance.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] In many implementations, template files contain variables or placeholders that are replaced with data supplied by an application when the page is generated.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] The source code of the template engine can be proprietary or open source.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Many template systems are a component of a larger programming platform or framework.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] They are referred to as the "platform's template system".
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Some template systems have the option of substituting a different template language or engine.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Programming languages such as Perl, Ruby, C, and Java support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] JavaServer Pages (JSP), PHP, and Active Server Pages (ASP with VBScript, JScript or other languages) are examples, themselves, of web template engines.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] These technologies are typically used in server-side templating systems, but could be adapted for use on an "edge-side" proxy or for static page generation.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Static site generators are engines that use flat text input files like markdown and asciidoc to generate a static web page.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Examples of this include Jekyll (Liquid, Ruby), Hugo (Go templates), and Pelican (Jinja2, Python).
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Some hosted website builders, including Wix, Weebly, and Duda, provide template-based systems that allow users to create static and dynamic web pages through graphical user interfaces rather than traditional programming.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] HTML editors often use web template systems to produce only static web pages.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] These can be viewed as a ready-made web design, used to mass-produce "cookie-cutter" websites for rapid deployment.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] They also commonly include themes in place of CSS styles.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] In general, the template language is used only with the editor's software.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] FrontPage and Dreamweaver were once the most popular editors with template sub-systems.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] A Flash web template uses Macromedia Flash to create visually interactive sites.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Many *server-side template systems* have an option to publish output pages on the server, where the published pages are static.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] This is common on content management systems, like Vignette, but is not considered out-server generation.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] In the majority of cases, this "publish option" doesn't interfere with the *template system*, and it can be made by external software, as Wget.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] People began to use server-side dynamic pages generated from templates with pre-existent software adapted for this task.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] This early software was the preprocessors and macro languages, adapted for the web use, running on CGI.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Next, a simple but relevant technology was the direct execution made on extension modules, started with SSI.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Technically, the methodology of embedding programming languages within HTML (or XML, etc.), used in many "server-side included script languages" are also templates.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] All of them are Embedded complex languages.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] There are also preprocessors used as server-side template engines.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] As for edge-side template and inclusion systems, "edge-side" refers to web servers that reside in the space between the client (browser) and the originating server.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] They are often referred to as "reverse-proxy" servers.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] These servers are generally tasked with reducing the load and traffic on originating servers by caching content such as images and page fragments, and delivering this to the browser in an efficient manner.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Basic Edge Side Includes (ESI) is an SSI-like language.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] ESI has been implemented for content delivery networks.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] The ESI template language may also be implemented in web browsers using JavaScript and Ajax, or via a browser "plug-in".
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] Many web browsers can apply an XSLT stylesheet to XML data that transforms the data into an XHTML document, thereby providing template functionality in the browser itself.
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] The most simple form is transclusions (HTML frames).
[src:jinja-templating/web-template-system] In other cases dynamic web pages are needed.
